@Node Configuration "SkandalfoClock: How to adjust the thing"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is configured changing its icon tooltypes. There's no other way to configure it (neither prefs-file or prefs editor). Even if it's launched from a CLI or Shell it searches for the icon for getting the parameters. If a parameter doesn't appear or the icon is not found the parameter will take the default value.

The available tooltypes are:

@{fg highlight}HOMEDIR:@{fg text} This will make @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} change its current directory to the path specified, so all paths specified in any other tooltype will be relative to this. Useful for placing @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} in WBStartup. Default: @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} doesn't change its current directory.

@{fg highlight}BACKDROP:@{fg text} This will make @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} to open its window as a backdrop window. When you select this you won't be able to move or resize the window. Default: not specified.

@{fg highlight}FIXED:@{fg text} This will make @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window fixed, that is, not movable nor sizeable. Default: not specified.

@{fg highlight}LEFTEDGE:@{fg text} This will set @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window left edge position. Default: 0.

@{fg highlight}TOPEDGE:@{fg text} This will set @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window top edge position. Default: 0.

@{fg highlight}WIDTH:@{fg text} This will set @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window width. Default: 100.

@{fg highlight}HEIGHT:@{fg text} This will set @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window height. Default: 100.

@{fg highlight}BORDER:@{fg text} May take the values: NONE for no borders, SINGLE for single line borders or DOUBLE for double borders. Default: DOUBLE.

@{fg highlight}RECESSED:@{fg text} If specified inverts the shine/shadow of the border lines. Default: not specified.

@{fg highlight}BACKTYPE:@{fg text} May take the values COLOUR for a solid colour, IMAGE for a datatypes image or TRANSPARENT for a transparent clock. If you select COLOUR the background will take the colour specified by @{fg highlight}BACKCOLOUR@{fg text}. If you select IMAGE the image loaded will be taken from the tooltype @{fg highlight}BACKFILE@{fg text}. Default: COLOUR.

@{fg highlight}BACKCOLOUR:@{fg text} Specification for background colour if @{fg highlight}BACKTYPE@{fg text} was set to COLOUR. Defaults to #0.

@{fg highlight}BACKFILE:@{fg text} Path for file used for background image if @{fg highlight}BACKTYPE@{fg text} was set to IMAGE. Any datatypes readable image may be used. Default: none (it falls back to COLOUR).

@{fg highlight}OVAL:@{fg text} If specified marks for twelve, quarters, hours and minutes conform to a circle. Else they conform to the window rectangle. Default: not specified.

@{fg highlight}BORDERWIDTH:@{fg text} Number of pixels between vertical lines of window borders when @{fg highlight}BORDER@{fg text} is set to DOUBLE. Default: 1.

@{fg highlight}BORDERHEIGHT:@{fg text} Number of pixels between horizontal lines of window borders when @{fg highlight}BORDER@{fg text} is set to DOUBLE. Default: 1.

@{fg highlight}SHOW:@{fg text} Selects which marks appear on @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s window. Set it to NOTHING for nothing, TWELVE for only the twelve mark, QUARTERS for twelve and quarters, HOURS for twelve, quarters and hours, or MINUTES for twelve, quarters, hours and minutes. Default: HOURS.

@{fg highlight}NOSECOND:@{fg text} If specified the hand that shows the seconds won't appear. Default: not specified.

@{fg highlight}HOUR1, MINUTE1, SECOND1, TWELVE1, QUARTERS1, HOURS1, MINUTES1:@{fg text} Set the colours for filling the hands and marks. Default: too lazy to copy them :)

@{fg highlight}HOUR2, MINUTE2, SECOND2, TWELVE2, QUARTERS2, HOURS2, MINUTES2:@{fg text} Set the colours for outlining the hands and marks. Default: too lazy to copy them :)

@{fg highlight}HOURFIG, MINUTEFIG, SECONDFIG, TWELVEFIG, QUARTERSFIG, HOURSFIG, MINUTESFIG:@{fg text} Set the file name for @{" vector files " LINK Figs} used to define the shapes of the hands and the marks. Default: PROGDIR:Data/(Hour|Minute|Second|Twelve|Quarters|Hours|Minutes).fig.

@{fg highlight}CHIMES:@{fg text} This sets the mode for the chimes. Use NONE for no chimes, SINGLE for a single chime each quarter or hourm MULTIPLE for a number of quarter chimes each quarter and a number of hour chimes each hour (12:30 -> 2 quarter chimes; 16:00 -> 4 quarter chimes + 4 hour chimes). Default: NONE.

@{fg highlight}HOURSOUND:@{fg text} Specifies the filename of a datatypes sample used for the hour chimes. Default: none (no sound is produced).

@{fg highlight}QUARTERSOUND:@{fg text} Specifies the filename of a datatypes sample used for the quarter chimes. Default: none (no sound is produced).

@{fg highlight}PUBSCREEN:@{fg text} Specifies a public screen name for @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} to open its window on. If it is "Workbench" @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} will open and close its window when required for a WB preferences change (screennotify.library should be properly installed). Default: Workbench.

@{fg highlight}SIZEASPICTURE:@{fg text} When specified and @{fg highlight}BACKTYPE@{fg text} is IMAGE the window size will be taken from the background image size.

@{fg highlight}ALARMSOUND:@{fg text} Specifies the filename of a datatypes sample used for the alarm. Default: none (no sound is produced).

@{fg highlight}ALARMCYCLES:@{fg text} Specifies how many times the @{fg highlight}ALARMSOUND@{fg text} sample will be played when the alarm triggers. Note that it only works with some samples (no idea why). Default: 1.

@{fg highlight}SHOWDATE:@{fg text} Set it to NONE (no date will be printed in the clock), NORMAL (one colour text) or SHADOW (one colour over another colour shadow). Default: NONE.

@{fg highlight}DATEPEN:@{fg text} Set the colour for date text. Default: Index #2.

@{fg highlight}DATESHADOW:@{fg text} Set the colour for date shadow. Default: Index #1.

@{fg highlight}DATEFONT:@{fg text} Set the font for the date. Default: topaz.font.

@{fg highlight}DATEFONTSIZE:@{fg text} Set the font size for the date. Default: 8.

For giving the colours, there are two ways:

@{fg highlight}#<number>@{fg text} defines colour as the index <number> of the public screen.

@{fg highlight}<R>,<G>,<B>@{fg text} defines colour as the RGB triplet given (it will be allocated).
@EndNode

@Node Usage "SkandalfoClock: How to use a clock"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} works like any other analogue clock. After configuring it via tooltypes (see @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}) run it and its window will open. If dragging is enabled, you will be able to drag the window clicking inside it. Click in the bottom right corner to resize it. Press ESCAPE to quit it, or use the menus.

There is a "Settings" menu for setting the alarm (a little window opens) and turning it on or off.
@EndNode

@Node Figs "SkandalfoClock: Make your own clock hands"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s hands may be customized by the user. The only thing you need is to write a new vector file for each hand/mark you want to change.

These Files take the form:

@{fg highlight}<start of file>@{fg text}
x0 y0
x1 y1
.. ..
.. ..
.. ..
xN yN
@{fg highlight}<end of file>@{fg text}

Where the pairs (xi,yi) are the coordinates of the vertexes of the shape you want to use. The coordinates go from (-256,-256) to (256,256), being these ones the opposite corners of the window. Take a look at the supplied vector files to get an idea about the useful ranges.

If you want to make a rectangle with the fourth part of the area of the window and centered, it would be something like:

@{fg highlight}<start of file>@{fg text}
-128 -128
 128 -128
 128  128
-128  128
@{fg highlight}<end of file>@{fg text}

Note that you should design the shape pointing up (towards (0,-256). Although the tooltypes (see @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}) let you change the marks for the quarters, hours and minutes, which appear rotated on the window, you should design these pointing up, too. @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} will rotate them.
@EndNode

@Node History "SkandalfoClock: Once upon a time there was a clock..."
@{fg highlight}1.0:@{fg text}
     Initial release.
@{fg highlight}1.1:@{fg text}
     Changed window refreshing slightly.
     Fixed two Enforcer hits (one of them was a stupid thing making Enforcer jump each second). Hope they were all. Thanks Mat of elveneeleven.
     Fixed Slider problem in Set Alarm window.
     Made Sliders update the Alarm Time text while dragged.
     Added HOMEDIR tooltype.
     Fixed some problems with transparent backgrounds.
     Added date displaying in main window (and relative tooltypes).
     Added new catalogs that people sent me.
@EndNode

@Node Future "SkandalfoClock: The future: ARexx macro language for time travelling..."
Well, I think @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is a mostly finished program, and probably there won't be any more versions unless a serious bug is found. Anyway if I get some interesting suggestions perhaps I'll program them into @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}, who knows?

Perhaps I'll make a little program for making @{" vector files " LINK Figs}. Perhaps.
@EndNode

@Node Installation "SkandalfoClock: Where to put each file..."
Well, I'm too lazy to write another installer script (I already wrote one for @{b}SkandalfoCDP@{ub}). There are two possible methods to install @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}:

(I).- (Not Recommended) Copy the entire drawer where you like and then make (soft) links from the directory SYS:WBStartup to @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}'s executable and icon. In this way you won't have to specify the paths for @{" vector files " LINK Figs}, because PROGDIR: will refer to the directory where the real executable resides. Good trick, isn't it?

(II).- (Not Recommended) Do as (I), but @{u}copy@{uu} the executable and its icon to SYS:WBStartup. Then edit all the tooltypes that give a path and set them to absolute paths or paths through an assign like "SkClock:" (you should then insert the correct assignment command into your S:User-Startup). Also copy the corresponding catalogs files (if necessary) to LOCALE:Catalogs.

(III).- (New for V1.1, Strongly Recommended) Copy the entire drawer where you like and the executable and its icon to SYS:WBStartup. Also copy the catalog file you prefer to LOCALE:catalogs/<languagename>/. Then set the tooltype (in the icon in SYS:WBStartup) @{fg highlight}HOMEDIR@{fg text} to the directory where you have copied all files. All paths will be relative to this.

After any of these change the tooltypes to your likes (see @{" Configuration " LINK Configuration}).

Yes, I know it's a somewhat sluggish installation, but you are going to do it only once, aren't you?

@{u}NOTE@{uu}: For method (I) I recommend MakeLink and FixSoftLinks packages found in Aminet and made by Todd Vierling.
@EndNode

@Node Copyright "SkandalfoClock: Copyright notice"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is Copyright © 1997 Juan J. García de Soria Lucena, all rights reserved.

@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is freely distributable as long as no charge is made other than to cover copying and media costs. The files in this distribution must be kept together and unchanged in their original form (only repacking is allowed). Aminet and Meeting Pearls are given permission to include @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} in their CD's.

You may use the sources of @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} as a learning example. You may even include parts of @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} in your programs, but those programs may not be distributed if you don't note somewhere in your distribution the original work of the author.

Note that @{b}this program is distributed "AS IS" and without any warranty.@{ub} The author won't be liable to you for any damage the program may do to your computer or your data if it proves to be faulty. @{b}YOU USE IT AT YOUR OWN RISK.@{ub}

@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is @{fg highlight}(EMAIL|CARD)WARE@{fg text}. This means that if you decide to keep using @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} after testing it you must send an e-mail or a postcard to the author. After that you may use @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} for free. This is because I like to know how many people is using my programs, and because I like getting postcards from different countries. So I'll prefer postcards, but I'll be satisfied with a brief e-mail.

Also you could send me other things like money (if you (ha ha ha) think I deserve it), a program you have done (or a keyfile, again if you think I deserve that), a t-shirt of your preferred TV-series, a novel, a 060 accelerator board for an A1200, suggestions, bug reports, or something so that I'll know that you're using @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}.
@EndNode

@Node Introduction "SkandalfoClock: Why?"
There's a lot of analog clocks available for Amiga computers. Why did I write another one?

Well. It was time ago that I got a nice analog clock. The version I got was crippled Shareware: it wouldn't let you save all the settings unless you registered it, so the most interesting features were lost.

As I don't consider a nifty clock to be an essential part of an operating environment I said "What a pity!" and forgot the program. That's because I'm only an student, without any fixed income, so when I get some money I don't use it to buy every small program someone has written.

A lot of time after that, after ESCOM and AT went down, I got Amiga Developer CD, and I learned to write MUIless programs (yes, that was a great step ahead :), so I thought I would be able to write a small analog clock program with all the features of that clock and perhaps some new ones, so that I wouldn't have to register ;-)

And @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} is the result. It does the same things that that clock did, and some that it didn't (samples for chimes and alarm, user-definable hand shapes, RGB colours, locale support), although the configuration is rather hard. Anyway you are going to configure it only once, aren't you?

@{fg highlight}IMPORTANT NOTE:@{fg text}
A previous distribution of this AmigaGuide document stated that @{b}TolleUhr@{ub}, by by M. Fleischer and G. Nikl, was crippled shareware. That is totally FALSE, as @{b}TolleUhr@{ub} has ever been released as FREEWARE. Thanks to its authors for making me note that misinformation. Surely I got a "two clocks" confusion.
@EndNode

@Node Features "SkandalfoClock: What does it do?"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} has plenty of features:

        · Configurable window type: backdrop/fixed/normal.
        
        · Configurable window background: colour/image/transparent.
        
        · Configurable window borders.
        
        · Configurable colours for hands, background and marks, both with index number or RGB.
        
        · Configurable hand shapes via vector files.
        
        · Chimes for hours and quarters, both single and multiple, with datatypes sampled sounds.
        
        · Alarm, with datatype sound.
        
        · Automatic window opening/closing when WB preferences change.
        
        · Locale support.
        
        · MUIless (he he, that's indeed a feature :-).
        
        · 34kB size executable (well, it's rather big).
        
        · It's @{fg highlight}(EMAIL|CARD)WARE@{fg text}! (Almost free).
@EndNode

@Node Requirements "SkandalfoClock: What do you need?"
@{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} needs:

        · An Amiga computer. It won't run on a PeeCee (at most it will crawl in an emulated Amiga).
        
        · AmigaOS 3.0+. It won't work with Macrosoft Winslows.
        
        · About 100kB free RAM. It doesn't require 32MB EDO RAM.
        
        · screennotify.library in LIBS: if you want @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} to auto open/close it window when WB preference change.
@EndNode

@Node Bugs "SkandalfoClock: Bugs? No, thank you."
I have tried to program @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} in a clean and system-conform style. Anyway after testing I have found the following undesired behaviours:

        · When in the Set Alarm window, sometimes the text and clock updating stops when you move a slider. I wasn't able to find the problem, but it appears to have more to do with gadtools TEXT_KIND class.
        
        · When the About Requester is brought up the other windows stop until you cancel it. This isn't exactly a bug. Simply I don't know how to avoid it yet. @{fg highlight}FIXED in V1.1.@{fg text}

        · @{fg highlight}ALARMCYCLES@{fg text} tooltype seems to work only with some sound samples. I don't know why it happens. I think it's a datatypes-related problem.
        
        · I don't know why, but @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub} consumes more CPU time when its window is bigger. Supossedly all drawing is done with the Blitter! It happens also with the clock that comes with Workbench?

In the case that you find a bug in @{b}SkandalfoClock@{ub}, please contact me.
@EndNode

